HTML – Interview Revision Notes

1. What is HTML
HTML (HyperText Markup Language) defines the structure of a web page.
It is not a programming language; it is a markup language.
Current standard: HTML5.



2. Basic HTML Structure
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Document</title>
</head>
<body>
  Content
</body>
</html>

DOCTYPE tells the browser that the document follows HTML5 standards.
Head contains metadata.
Body contains visible content.



3. Semantic HTML
Semantic elements describe meaning and structure.

header  -> top section
nav     -> navigation
main    -> main content
section -> logical grouping
article -> independent content
aside   -> sidebar
footer  -> footer content

Benefits:
Better SEO
Better accessibility
Readable and maintainable code



4. Block vs Inline Elements

Block Elements:
Take full width
Start on new line
Examples: div, p, h1-h6, section, article

Inline Elements:
Take only required width
Examples: span, a, img, strong, em




5. Attributes
Provide additional information to elements.

Common attributes:
id (unique)
class (reusable)
src, href
alt (accessibility)
title
data-*



6. Forms and Input Elements

Important input types:
text
email
password
checkbox
radio
submit

Important attributes:
name
value
placeholder
required
readonly
disabled
pattern



7. HTML5 Input Types
email
number
date
time
range
file
color



8. Meta Tags
Used for SEO and responsive design.

description
keywords
viewport (important for mobile responsiveness)

          

9. Accessibility (A11y)
Use semantic HTML
Always use alt for images
Use label with input
Use aria attributes when needed



10. HTML Entities
Used to display reserved characters.

&lt;   <
&gt;   >
&amp;  &
&nbsp; space



11. Multimedia
audio and video tags allow native media embedding.

Important attributes:
controls
autoplay
loop
muted


          

12. iframe
Used to embed external content like videos or web pages.


          

13. Script vs Link
script tag is used for JavaScript.
link tag is used for CSS.

          

14. Inline vs Internal vs External
Inline: inside the tag (not recommended)
Internal: inside style or script tag
External: separate file (best practice)


          

15. HTML vs HTML5

HTML:
Limited semantic tags
No native audio/video

HTML5:
Rich semantic tags
Native audio and video support
Better accessibility
LocalStorage and SessionStorage support


          
16. Common Interview Questions
Difference between div and span
What is semantic HTML?
Why is alt attribute important?
Block vs inline elements
Purpose of doctype
Difference between id and class



          

17. Best Practices
Use semantic tags
Proper indentation
Avoid inline styling
Always write accessible and SEO-friendly HTML
